.TH ZFPING 8 "2026-06-18" "zfping 0.1.2" "System Manager's Manual"
.SH NAME
zfping \- send ICMP ECHO_REQUEST packets to network hosts (Zig port of fping)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B zfping
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ targets ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B zfping
is a pure-Zig, fping-compatible program to send ICMP echo probes to network
hosts, similar to
.BR ping (8),
but performing much better when pinging multiple hosts. Unlike
.BR ping ,
.B zfping
is meant to be used in scripts and monitoring systems, so its output is
designed to be easy to parse. Options, output formats and exit codes mirror
.BR fping (8);
known divergences are documented in the project CHANGELOG.
.PP
.B zfping
moves to the next target after each probe instead of waiting for a reply
(round-robin), paces all transmissions globally and per subnet, and caps the
number of outstanding probes \(em it is built for high-volume monitoring
(10k+ host checks per cycle) without bursting probes into one network branch.
.PP
Targets are read from the command line, from a file
.RB ( \-f ),
generated from a range or CIDR
.RB ( \-g ),
or \(em when none are given \(em from standard input. Targets may be IPv4 or
IPv6 addresses (including link-local with scope ids, e.g.
.IR fe80::1%eth0 )
or host names.
.SH PROBING OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-4 ", " \-\-ipv4
Restrict name resolution and pinging to IPv4 addresses.
.TP
.BR \-6 ", " \-\-ipv6
Restrict name resolution and pinging to IPv6 addresses.
.TP
.BI \-b\  BYTES \fR,\ \fB\-\-size= BYTES
Amount of ping data to send, in bytes (default: 56). The IP and ICMP headers
are added on top.
.TP
.BI \-B\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-backoff= N
Exponential backoff factor applied to the timeout after each retry
(default: 1.5).
.TP
.BI \-c\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-count= N
Count mode: send
.I N
pings to each target and report per-target statistics at the end.
.TP
.BI \-f\  FILE \fR,\ \fB\-\-file= FILE
Read the list of targets from a file
.RI ( \- " means standard input)."
.TP
.BR \-g ", " \-\-generate
Generate the target list from a start/end address pair or a CIDR network
(e.g. \fBzfping \-g 192.168.1.0 192.168.1.255\fR or
\fBzfping \-g 192.168.1.0/24\fR). IPv4 prefixes shorter than /31 exclude the
network and broadcast addresses; at most 131072 targets may be generated.
.TP
.BI \-H\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-ttl= N
Set the IP TTL (time to live / hop limit) on outgoing probes.
.TP
.BI \-i\  MSEC \fR,\ \fB\-\-interval= MSEC
Minimum interval between any two outgoing packets, in milliseconds
(default: 10). This is the global send pacing.
.TP
.BI \-I\  IFACE \fR,\ \fB\-\-iface= IFACE
Bind the sockets to a particular interface (SO_BINDTODEVICE; requires
CAP_NET_RAW).
.TP
.BI \-\-oiface= IFACE
Send probes via a specific outgoing interface (IP_PKTINFO) while accepting
replies from any interface.
.TP
.BI \-k\  FWMARK \fR,\ \fB\-\-fwmark= FWMARK
Set the routing mark on outgoing packets (requires CAP_NET_ADMIN).
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-loop
Loop mode: send pings forever, until interrupted.
.TP
.BR \-m ", " \-\-all
Use all addresses a hostname resolves to (e.g. IPv4 and IPv6), not just the
first one. Use together with
.BR \-A .
.TP
.BR \-M ", " \-\-dontfrag
Set the Don't Fragment flag (path MTU discovery).
.TP
.BI \-O\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-tos= N
Set the type of service / traffic class on outgoing probes.
.TP
.BI \-p\  MSEC \fR,\ \fB\-\-period= MSEC
Interval between probes to one target in loop and count modes, in
milliseconds (default: 1000).
.TP
.BI \-r\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-retry= N
Number of retries before a target is considered unreachable (default: 3).
.TP
.BR \-R ", " \-\-random
Fill the ping payload with random data (to defeat link-layer compression).
.TP
.BI \-S\  IP \fR,\ \fB\-\-src= IP
Set the source address of outgoing probes.
.TP
.BI \-\-seqmap\-timeout= MSEC
Accepted for fping compatibility; this port frees sequence slots when the
probe timeout fires, so the option has no observable effect.
.TP
.BI \-t\  MSEC \fR,\ \fB\-\-timeout= MSEC
Initial per-probe timeout in milliseconds (default: 500; in loop/count modes
the
.B \-p
period, capped at 2000).
.TP
.B \-\-check\-source
Discard replies whose source address does not match the target address.
.TP
.B \-\-icmp\-timestamp
Send ICMP Timestamp requests (RFC 792) instead of ICMP Echo. IPv4 only;
requires a raw socket (CAP_NET_RAW or root).
.SH OUTPUT OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-alive
Show only targets that are alive.
.TP
.BR \-A ", " \-\-addr
Show targets by address. Combined with
.B \-n
or
.BR \-d ,
targets are shown as "name (address)".
.TP
.BI \-C\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-vcount= N
Same as
.BR \-c ,
but report the individual round-trip times in a per-target table instead of
summary statistics.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-rdns
Show targets by name, forcing a reverse-DNS lookup for every target.
.TP
.BR \-D ", " \-\-timestamp
Print a timestamp before each output line.
.TP
.BI \-\-timestamp\-format= FORMAT
Timestamp format for
.BR \-D :
.BR ctime ", " iso " or " rfc3339
(default: Unix epoch seconds).
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-elapsed
Show the elapsed (round-trip) time on returned packets.
.TP
.BR \-J ", " \-\-json
Output results in JSON format (requires
.BR \-c ", " \-C " or " \-l ).
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-name
Show targets by name: numeric targets are reverse-resolved, host names are
kept as given.
.TP
.BR \-N ", " \-\-netdata
Output in netdata chart format (use with
.BR \-l " and " \-Q ).
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-outage
Show the accumulated outage time (lost packets \(mu packet interval).
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Quiet: suppress per-target/per-probe results, print only final summaries.
.TP
.BI \-Q\  SECS \fR[\fB,cumulative\fR],\ \fB\-\-squiet= SECS \fR[\fB,cumulative\fR]
Like
.BR \-q ,
but print an interval summary every
.I SECS
seconds. With
.BR cumulative ,
statistics count from the beginning instead of per interval.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-stats
Print cumulative statistics for the whole run.
.TP
.BR \-u ", " \-\-unreach
Show only targets that are unreachable.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Show version information.
.TP
.BI \-x\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-reachable= N
Report whether at least
.I N
hosts are reachable; the exit status reflects the result.
.TP
.BI \-X\  N \fR,\ \fB\-\-fast\-reachable= N
Exit immediately with success as soon as
.I N
hosts have answered.
.TP
.B \-\-print\-tos
Show the received TOS / traffic class value.
.TP
.B \-\-print\-ttl
Show the received TTL / hop limit value.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show usage information.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
.B 0
All targets (or at least the number requested with
.BR \-x / \-X )
are reachable.
.TP
.B 1
Some targets were unreachable, or a usage error occurred. (fping documents
exit 3 for invalid arguments, but its binary exits 1 on every usage error;
.B zfping
matches the binary.)
.TP
.B 2
Some addresses could not be resolved.
.TP
.B 4
Internal error (e.g. socket permissions).
.SH PERMISSIONS
.B zfping
first tries an unprivileged SOCK_DGRAM ICMP socket, then falls back to
SOCK_RAW. For monitoring daemons, allow unprivileged ping sockets:
.PP
.nf
    sysctl \-w net.ipv4.ping_group_range="0 2147483647"
.fi
.PP
or grant the binary the raw-socket capability:
.PP
.nf
    setcap cap_net_raw+ep zfping
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
zfping \-c 3 \-i 5 192.0.2.1 2001:db8::1
zfping \-g 192.168.1.0/24 \-a \-q
zfping \-l \-p 1000 \-Q 10 \-N gateway1 gateway2
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR fping (8),
.BR ping (8)
.PP
